"depressionExercisesAdvancedPopupBody" : "These activities make up your main workout. They are supposed to increase your heart rate and breathing. Doing these will also boost your mood and energy levels.
 
Burpees are a full-body cardio-strength exercise. This means that doing a burpee strengthens and conditions your body, while also giving you a cardio workout. Burpees not only increase physical strength but can also help you develop mental toughness and discipline.
 
Crunches are one of the most commonly practised abdomen exercises. They target your abdominal muscles and sides, providing strength and definition. Doing crunches can also help you slow down and refocus your attention.
 
Push ups are a strength-training exercise done in a horizontal position. They improve your posture and increase abdominal and upper arm strength. They can also protect your shoulder and lower back from injuries."

"depressionExercisesCoolingDownPopUpBody" : "Cool down activities help you stretch out your muscles and bring your body back to a state of calm.
 
Neck stretch is an exercise focussed on maintaining stability and flexibility in your body. It can reduce tension in your muscles and can ease any pain you might be experiencing. It also helps in preventing any injury from the exercise session.
 
Front thigh stretch is an exercise which specifically relaxes your lower body and helps in preventing injuries. Doing this reduces soreness, strengthens your lower body, and helps you stay flexible 
 
The cat-cow stretch is a yoga-based exercise. It is an excellent way to calm your body and bring it to a state of rest after a workout. It increases focus, coordination and flexibility. It also relieves stress and promotes emotional stability."

"depressionExercisesExerciseInfoPopUpBody" : "When people hear the word "exercise", they typically think of working out in a gym. While that is definitely one way to exercise, there are different activities you can engage in at home to get yourself active. The point of exercising is to make your body active so that you can stay physically healthy.
 
A study found that people who engage even in low intensity, non-sweat inducing work outs are less likely to feel depressed than people who are sedentary. Exercising can lower stress levels. It releases dopamine, a neurochemical that makes you feel happier and causes feelings of euphoria. In fact, being active can also make you feel more confident about yourself. 
 
These benefits of exercise can only be experienced when you find the right kinds of activities to engage in. Over-exercising or exercising the wrong way can cause strain on your body and can even cause injuries. On the other hand, doing easy exercises when in fact your body can do much more might not have any impact on you at all. That's why we tried to determine how much you currently exercise. 
 
Before you actually start exercising, it's important to warm your body up. This prepares your muscles for more strenuous exercises you might engage in. Finally, once you are done, engaging in some cool-down exercises can make it easier for your body to transition from exercising to not exercising."

"depressionMasteryPopupText" : "A common symptom of depression is lack of interest in daily activities. This can demotivate you to carry out any activity in the day, which in turn can make you feel lethargic. On the other hand, not doing anything in the day can make your mood worse. "depressionPleasurableBrDialogText1" : "One of the core symptoms of depression is the inability to enjoy activities that were previously fun for you. In clinical language, this symptom is known as anhedonia which translates to the inability to feel pleasure. As result, you might feel demotivated to carry out any activity and might become lethargic.

But experts say - and studies have proved - that the way to feel better is by engaging in action. In other words, unless you do some activity to uplift your mood, you will continue to feel worse.

This activity teaches you a technique called activity scheduling. The goal is to get you to do something that you find fun or enjoyable. Doing something that gives you a sense of pleasure is helpful because it can lift your mood. This can then motivate you to try out other things that can help you overcome depression."

"depressionPleasurableBrDialogText2" : "It can be really hard to think of activities that are fun or enjoyable when you are feeling low. But here are a few tips that might help.

Think back to a time when you weren't feeling as low as you are now. What did you enjoy doing? What were some activities that you used to make you feel happy? Are you still doing any of those activities now? They can act as sources of fun for you.

Another way to identify fun activities is to think of activities that you look forward to. If you look forward to something, it means you feel excited by it - and that's great!

Finally, you can also check if any activity you do in the day feels effortless for you. Do you feel like time has passed by very quickly while doing an activity? This activity, again, is likely to be an activity that you enjoy doing."

"graphDialogAngerBody1" : "If you are someone who gets angry very frequently, it is possible that you may not know what exactly has caused your anger. You may also not understand the warning signs of your anger and may find yourself losing control and having a sudden angry outburst."

"graphDialogAngerBody2" : "Most people who have anger problems find it difficult to calm down once they start getting angry. You may take a long time to let go of your anger and relax yourself. This in turn can worsen your anger."

"graphDialogAngerBody3" : "Mindfulness involves being fully aware of the present moment and having a non-judgemental attitude towards others and yourself. When you feel angry you may find it very difficult to do both. Anger can cause arousal in terms of increased heart rate and rapid breathing. This may not allow you to focus on the present moment."

"graphDialogAngerBody4" : "Rumination refers to constantly thinking about a situation which caused you anger. Every time you rethink the situation, you might end up feeling more angry. Even though you are reflecting on the situation, you are most likely not gaining any new insights. Instead, you are just experiencing emotional and psychological distress."

"graphDialogAngerBody5" : "Anger can affect your ability to communicate. When you feel angry your mind is unable to process information efficiently. Anger also causes a strong emotional reaction in you as well as those around you. This prevents communication from taking place smoothly."

"graphDialogAngerBody6" : "Anger can distort your view of the world and lead to a lot of negative thoughts. These unhelpful thoughts can cause you to have a negative perception of everything around you. You are also likely to misunderstand or misinterpret a situation, which leads to even more anger."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody1" : "Worrying can be a good thing at times. It can help you avoid dangerous situations and live a healthier life. However, when you deal with anxiety, you may find yourself worrying excessively even when there does not seem to be any reason."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody2" : "This is the inability to fully experience unpleasant or uncomfortable emotions and is accompanied by a desperate need to avoid such emotions. When you feel anxious you may develop an intense fear or aversion to negative emotions and may not want to experience them."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody3" : "When you feel anxious you tend to hold on to tension and stress in your muscles. This can cause pain, discomfort and trouble with mobility. This can be a vicious cycle as certain movements can lead to pain in other parts of the body, and this physical discomfort in turn can make you feel even more anxious."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody4" : "Anxiety causes a stress response in the brain and body. This causes your heart rate to increase and your blood to be diverted to your limbs rather than your brain. This impairs your perception and other cognitive abilities. As a result, you might find it difficult to concentrate on the task at hand."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody5" : "Mindfulness involves being fully aware of the present moment and having a non-judgemental attitude towards others and yourself. When you feel anxious you may find it very difficult to do both. This is especially because anxiety is deeply rooted in the fear of what will happen in the future, and thus you may not be able to focus on the present moment."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody6" : "The anxious brain is always vigilant and looking for anything that can he perceived as dangerous or threatening. This can cause you to have constant negative thoughts about what could happen in the future. You may also end up comparing yourself to others or having panic attacks."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody7" : "When you feel anxious you may constantly worry about your own thoughts. You may realise that worrying to this extent can be harmful for you, and yet you do not know how to stop worrying. This can cause you to feel even more worried and anxious."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody8" : "Anxiety can cause you to have negative thoughts about yourself. This can make you doubt yourself; you may feel uncomfortable with decisions you make. You may also find yourself predicting the worst possible outcome for all possible solutions to a problem and may be unable to decide which solution to implement."

"graphDialogAnxietyBody9" : "Anxiety is an unpleasant experience. It is likely that you would like to relieve yourself of the unpleasant feeling and would prefer not to participate in anything which can trigger your anxiety. In order to do this you may begin avoiding things that you believe will trigger your anxiety. This avoidance reduces your anxiety in the short term but in the long term makes your anxiety worse."

"graphDialogBodyAnger" : "Anger is an intense negative emotion that you experience towards someone or something when you feel that you have been deliberately wronged. Excessive anger can cause many emotional, physical, cognitive and behavioural problems."

"graphDialogBodyAnxiety" : "Anxiety is persistent and intense worry or fear about everyday events or situations. It can lead to excessive nervousness, worry and unhappiness. While anxiety is a normal emotion, you can suffer from many physical and emotional problems if you regularly feel disproportionate levels of anxiety."

"graphDialogBodyDepression" : "Depression is a common mental health disorder that negatively affects how you feel, the way you think and how you act. It can lead to a variety of emotional and physical problems. Depending on its severity, depression can also decrease a person's ability to function at work and at home."

"graphDialogBodyHappiness" : "Happiness is a mental or emotional states which includes positive or pleasant emotions ranging from contentment to intense joy. It also means your life satisfaction and well-being."

"graphDialogBodySleep" : "Sleep is an essential component of physical and mental health. Getting good quality sleep consistently and regularly is necessary for your functioning. People who have difficulty sleeping well or have poor sleep quality may face numerous issues - both physically and mentally."

"graphDialogBodyStress" : "Stress is your body's physical, mental and emotional response to any changes in your environment, body or thought. While some amount of stress can be good for you, excessive stress can lead to a variety of emotional and physical problems."
"graphDialogDepressionBody1" : "One of the most frequently seen symptoms of depression is persistent low mood for weeks. This may manifest as feeling sad or empty, or crying often."

"graphDialogDepressionBody2" : "In depression, people often find that they are no longer interested in activities that used to give them a sense of pleasure or enjoyment. You may find yourself pulling away from your friends and family, or you might have stopped pursuing your hobbies. Any activity can seem tiring, hectic, and effortful."

"graphDialogDepressionBody3" : "Over 90% people who live with a mental health condition experience fatigue. Fatigue is characterised by extreme tiredness and low energy. It goes hand in hand with depression as depression affects neurotransmitters associated with alertness."

"graphDialogDepressionBody4" : "When you feel depressed, you may be unable to focus. Your concentration power diminishes, and you may have difficulty following instructions, remembering things, keeping track of conversations, making decisions and performing complicated tasks. You may also find yourself making careless mistakes, being forgetful and missing appointments."

"graphDialogDepressionBody5" : "Low self-esteem is characterised by a lack of confidence in yourself along with a belief that you are not worthy or important. Having such thoughts is common in depression, and this in turn can drastically worsen your mood."

"graphDialogDepressionBody6" : "These are negative thoughts which are largely untrue or irrational and automatically pop up when you feel stressed or are faced with a challenging situation. These thoughts are linked to chemical changes in your brain which cause you to feel low and upset."

"graphDialogHappinessBody1" : "The way you think about a situation can influence your emotional reaction to it. Positive thinking does not mean avoiding or ignoring the bad things, instead it means making the best of a bad situation and trying to see yourself and others in a positive light. It means approaching life's challenges with a positive outlook."

"graphDialogHappinessBody2" : "Positive psychology looks at gratitude not just as an act of expressing thanks but as a positive emotion. It is a deep appreciation for someone or something that creates long lasting positivity. It is one of the strongest correlates of happiness."

"graphDialogHappinessBody3" : "Mindfulness is a key factor for happiness. It means being fully aware of your environment as well as what you are experiencing. It involves observing yourself and your environment without getting caught up in thoughts. To be mindful is to accept what is happening without judgement. Mindfulness makes you healthier, less affected by stress, and more relaxed. It also improves your relationship with others and makes you more satisfied with life."

"graphDialogHappinessBody4" : "Social support is the physical and emotional comfort given to you by your friends, family, loved ones, co-workers, neighbours and acquaintances. It reminds you that you belong to a community of people who value you and care about your well-being. These social relationships play a critical role in how you function in your day to day life."

"graphDialogHappinessBody5" : "Life can be chaotic, demanding, confusing and painful. Understanding and accepting that life is made of both good and bad helps you have a balanced perspective. It gives you the strength to carry on during bad days when you may feel disappointed or demotivated. Applying balanced thinking helps you be emotionally at peace."

"graphDialogHappinessBody6" : "Resilience is your ability to bounce back from disaster, trauma or chaotic situations. It refers to how well you can adapt to changes in your life. A person who is more resilient and adaptable is more likely to be happier than one who is not very resilient."

"graphDialogHappinessBody7" : "This refers to having an understanding of the meaning of your life. It gives you a sense of purpose and fulfillment. Understanding the impact of what you do helps you enjoy what you do and become more satisfied with your life."

"graphDialogHappinessBody8" : "Self-competence is the feeling of being capable and in control. It is the belief that one will be successful in the future. To be self-competent is to view oneself as being worthy, capable, and effective. The key components of this self-competence are self-esteem, self-determination, and successful coping."

"graphDialogHappinessBody9" : "Positive emotions may be considered as any feeling where there is a lack of negativity, such that no pain or discomfort is felt. The most common positive emotions are joy, gratitude, serenity, interest, hope, pride, amusement, inspiration, awe and love."

"graphDialogSleepBody1" : "Lifestyle is one of the most crucial factors that affect sleep quality. Lifestyle habits are your daily behaviours which influence your ability to get sufficient high quality sleep. Problematic lifestyle factors include erratic work timings, irregular patterns of eating, drinking too much water, consuming caffeine or exercising too close to bedtime and using gadgets before bed."

"graphDialogSleepBody2" : "Your bedroom environment refers to the condition of the space you sleep in, and this is another factor that can cause poor sleep. Ideally, your room should be comfortable, cool, calm, dark, and not have any loud noises or bright lights. It should also be free of insects. A disturbance in your bedroom environment can very easily cause sleep difficulties."

"graphDialogSleepBody3" : "When sleep is disrupted for a long time, your mind may create a link between your bed and not sleeping. Whenever you come into contact with bed as a stimulus, your mind believes you must stay awake; thus your mind will prevent you from sleeping. Stimulus control helps in breaking you out of these associations and improving your sleep."

"graphDialogSleepBody4" : "When you lie down at the end of a long day you may still have the worries and anxieties of the day running through your mind. This can cause a state of hyperarousal where you have an increased rate of breathing and higher blood pressure. This can make it difficult for you to relax which can cause difficulty in falling asleep."

"graphDialogSleepBody5" : "If you have many negative thoughts running through your mind when you are trying to sleep it can prevent you from falling asleep. These thoughts hold your attention and can trigger a stress response in your body. Your brain believes you to be in the middle of an important situation and ensures that you remain awake. The part of your brain that controls your sleep does not realise that you are simply having negative thoughts. As a result, you brain maintains your vigilance to deal with the situation."

"graphDialogSleepBody6" : "This is one of the most common sleep problems. When you lie down to go to sleep at night, you may find that you cannot get sleep easily. It takes you a long time to fall asleep and you keep tossing and turning. The next morning, you do not feel fresh and feel tired throughout the day. When you finally get into bed you cannot wait to go to sleep as you feel tired. However, once again you are unable to get sleep and this becomes a vicious cycle of tired days and sleepless nights."

"graphDialogSleepBody7" : "Another commonly report sleep difficulty is inability to stay asleep. You may find yourself frequently waking up in the middle of the night and not being able to go back to sleep. As a result, you get disrupted sleep throughout the night."

"graphDialogSleepBody8" : "You may find yourself waking up much earlier than you actually intend to. This can cause emotional frustration and physical exhaustion. This can be due to change in your sleep cycle, hormones, or poor lifestyle."

"graphDialogSleepBody9" : "When you experience sleep difficulties, you may wake up feeling tired, groggy, and lethargic. From the moment you wake up, you may want to go back to sleep. You may feel unable to take part in activities, or may face challenges with concentration, memory, or emotional stability in the morning."

"graphDialogStressBody1" : "Most people feel a constant pressure to be productive. If you are highly stressed, you may feel guilty when you try to relax. You may even stress about not being able to relax. Scientific research suggests that when we stress about relaxing, or when we demand that our bodies do too much, we may simply not be able to let go. You may be unable to de-stress and relax because you are working too hard at relaxing."

"graphDialogStressBody2" : "When you feel stressed, you may be unable to focus. Your concentration power diminishes, and you may have difficulty following instructions, remembering things, keeping track of conversations, making decisions and performing complicated tasks. You may also find yourself making careless mistakes, being forgetful and missing appointments."

"graphDialogStressBody3" : "This is the inability to fully experience unpleasant or uncomfortable emotions; this is accompanied by a desperate need to avoid such emotions. When you feel stressed you may develop an intense fear of, or aversion to, negative emotions and may not want to experience them."

"graphDialogStressBody4" : "When you feel stressed, your brain is more reactive. You may end up limiting the options available to you or jumping to conclusions. When you are faced with less familiar conditions, you may try to narrow down and simplify your options instead of evaluating all options thoroughly. Your mind limits its functioning and this makes it difficult for you to solve problems."

"graphDialogStressBody5" : "In times of stress, you may be unable to delegate work to others and may not be aware of how long it takes to complete a task. This can cause you to take on more than you can handle and you may end up overextending yourself. This can cause you more stress and frustration."

"graphDialogStressBody6" : "This refers to the common phenomenon of being unable to or finding it difficult to explain to others your point of view. You may also withdraw or isolate yourself from others. You may also tend to misunderstand what another person is saying or what their intentions are when you are highly stressed."

"graphDialogStressBody7" : "Many people do not realise that their thoughts can influence the way they feel about situations. Your thoughts can become internal stressors or triggers and can cause extreme stress and worry within you."

playstore_details.title: InnerHour Self-Care Therapy - Anxiety & Depression
playstore_details.description:
Make time for self-care with the InnerHour app

Depression, anxiety, stress, and a host of other mental health concerns can stop you from leading your best possible life.

The InnerHour app is here to help!

Our psychiatrists and therapists are dedicated to your mental health. Using their insights from therapy along with the latest science in CBT (Cognitive Behaviour Therapy), Positive Psychology, and Mindfulness, they have replicated the real-life therapy experience into a self-help app for you.

Our ultimate aim is to support you to create a happier and healthier life with a range of therapy-based self-help tools and techniques designed for your mental health needs. 

Think of the app as your safe space for self-care. If you are looking for support to overcome depression, get anxiety relief, tackle stress, or simply experience happiness, the InnerHour app is for you!

▌Six self-help courses

Access therapy-based self-help tools for a range of mental health concerns:

• Depression: Make small changes to overcome depression
• Anxiety: Attain calm and balance with strategies for anxiety relief
• Sleep: Build a sleep schedule and develop habits to sleep soundly
• Stress: Keep a check on your stress levels to feel calm and in control
• Anger: Channelise your anger and build learn strategies to cool down 
• Happiness: Develop critical skills to experience happiness in life

▌Personalised 4-week plans

The app identifies your unique mental health needs and builds a personalised self-care plan in your area of concern - be it depression, anxiety, or stress.

Your self-help plan is a reflection of what happens in real life therapy. Over 4 weeks, you will learn and practise skills to battle depression, get anxiety relief, and lead a happier life.

So what does your plan entail?

1. Self-care activities

We have condensed decades of therapy experience and mental health research into short, simple activities - each teaching a strategy based on CBT, Positive Psychology, or Mindfulness. All you need is 5 minutes each day for self-care!

2. Goal setting and tracking

Our goal setting and tracking mechanism will help you build healthy habits that will last a lifetime. With this CBT-inspired feature, stay motivated to meet your physical and mental health goals, such as eating healthy, exercising, forming better relationships, and thinking positively.

3. Mood tracking

Our specialised tracker is a digital journal that will track how you are doing each day. The more you track, the more insights you will get! You can also map your mood to different activities you do throughout the day, in order to get finer insights.

4. InnerHour Resources

We want you to keep learning and growing on your self-help journey. Our resources include informative articles, easy tips, and inspiring quotes to help you stay motivated. For instance, you will:

• Understand the different causes of depression
• Learn about the symptoms of anxiety
• Know how to tell if it’s time to go to therapy

In addition to the plan, you can also access support from:

 • Allie - relief chatbot

Whenever you feel overwhelmed, you can talk to Allie, our intelligent chatbot. Allie identifies your specific mental health difficulty at the moment - be it intense anxiety or overwhelming depression - and offers support through simple activities that can help you feel calm immediately.

 • Qualified therapists

We know that sometimes, you might need a human touch on your self-help journey. In such times, you can reach out to an InnerHour expert for counselling, and get professional support for depression, anxiety, and even stress.

Small changes can make a big difference over time. Make yourself a priority, starting today!

For any questions, you can reach out to us on support@theinnerhour.com.

Visit our website: https://www.theinnerhour.com/
